ionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the name of the fabric, which is decorated with patterning of contrasting texture but the same colour. This is so called because it was originally imported from Damascus in Syria. Use as a first name may have been inspired by association with names such as   Dimity   and   Calico .  It may also have been adopted with reference to the distinctive dusky pink colour of the damask rose (<i>Rosa damascena</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>thorp(e)</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from any of several places called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["Short form of   Thornton   or transferred use of the surname (originally denoting someone who lived near a large thorn bush), or a direct adoption of the vocabulary word because of its association with natural hardiness. As a given name, this is recorded in England as early as the 16th century, but the modern name appears to have arisen in 19th-century America."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":21,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":30,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":65,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 